  "slug": "lebkuchen-christmas",
  "title": "Lebkuchen, German Christmas spice biscuits",
  "subtitle": "Honey-and-spice biscuits with a sugar-glaze top",
  "excerpt": "German lebkuchen in the Nuremberg household tradition: honey, dark sugar, ground almonds, candied peel and a strong dose of spice. Rolled, cut into rounds, baked soft, and finished with a thin sugar glaze. Twenty-four biscuits.",
  "type": "RECIPE",
  "sourceNotes": "Henriette Davidis, Praktisches Kochbuch (1845, public domain): documents the canonical German lebkuchen form. Hannah Glasse, The Art of Cookery (1747), Project Gutenberg: similar honey-and-spice biscuits appear in the cakes chapter as 'gingerbread of Lubec'. The pre-1928 trade gives the working ratio (one part honey to one part flour, by weight) used here.",
  "body": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Lebkuchen are German Christmas biscuits. Honey is the main sweetener. Warm the honey with brown sugar to a thin syrup, then pour it into a bowl of flour, ground almonds, mixed peel, and spice. Bring it together into a dough. Rest it in the fridge for at least 12 hours. The rest is not optional: without it the biscuits bake tough and the spices taste raw.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "The biscuit itself is soft rather than crisp, closer to a thick spiced cake than to a snap biscuit. A thin sugar-and-water glaze is brushed over the warm biscuits as they come from the oven; it dries to a fine matte shell.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
